ention of human intelligence in the application of law. Waldron defends thoughtfulness against the claim that it threatens to replace the rule of law with the arbitrary rule of people. To the contrary, he argues, the rule of law requires thoughtfulness: it is impossible to apply a standard such as “reasonableness” on the basis of rules alone, and common legal activities like arguing in court and reasoning from precedents are poorly served by algorithmic logics. This rich compilation also addresses the place of law in protecting human dignity, the relation between rule of law and legislation, and whether vagueness in the law is at odds with law’s role in guiding action.Thoughtfulness and the Rule of Law emphasizes the value of procedures rather than the substance or outcome of legal decisions. Challenging the view that predictability and clarity are cardinal virtues, Waldron shows that real-world controversies often are best approached using a relatively thin concept of the rule of law, together with the thoughtfulness that a legal system frames and enables.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLawxPhilosophy2DLC. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 0aLaw-Philosophy. 0aRule of law2DLC. 0aRule of law. 0aThoughtfulness2DLC. 0aThoughtfulness. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aagency.  aargument.  aconstitutionalism.  adiscretion.  adue process.  aefficacy.  afidelity.  afriedrich hayek.  ainternational.  ajoseph raz.  ajudges.  ajudicial review.  alegality.  apositivism.  apublic law.  aself application.  asovereignty.  astare decisis.  asupreme court.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part o